  <conclusion>
    <p>
      This collection of activities <ndash/> <xref text='title' ref="act-introductions"/>, <xref text='title' ref="SS_dot_pattern"/>, 
      <xref text='title' ref="act-growing-dots"/>, and <xref text='title' ref="act-graphing-dots"/> <ndash/> shows how 
      seemingly unrelated contexts and representations can have the same underlying mathematical structure. We see this a 
      lot in mathematics. Making these connections requires Brain Crossing (recall the video you watched today). Remember 
      that Brain Crossing helps you with recall and grows your brain!
    </p>
    <p>
      When you work on a new problem, try to connect the work you're doing to problems you've worked on in the past. Connecting related mathematics problems helps reduce your reliance on memorized procedures. It also helps move your working (short-term) memory into long-term memory so that it can be retrieved to help you make sense of new problems and concepts.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
